WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:16.070 --> 00:00:17.370
&gt;&gt; Mary Jane Deeb: Good
afternoon, everyone,

00:00:17.370 --> 00:00:20.160
and thank you all for coming.

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:24.540
I'm Mary Jane Deeb, Chief of
the African Release Division.

00:00:24.540 --> 00:00:27.660
And it's a great pleasure
to have you all here

00:00:27.660 --> 00:00:30.180
for what promises
to be a wonderful,

00:00:30.180 --> 00:00:32.700
wonderful presentation on Domes,

00:00:32.700 --> 00:00:39.380
Arches and Minarets
by Mr. Phil Pasquini.

00:00:39.380 --> 00:00:42.690
And I just want to
say a few words,

00:00:42.690 --> 00:00:49.220
as I do regarding what we
do here in the division.

00:00:49.220 --> 00:00:52.840
We're a division made up of
three sections; the African,

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:57.080
the Mideastern, and the
[inaudible] sections.

00:00:57.080 --> 00:01:03.320
And we are responsible for
78 countries in Africa,

00:01:03.320 --> 00:01:06.620
the Middle East, Central Asia,
the [inaudible] and responsible

00:01:06.620 --> 00:01:12.310
for many, many of the
languages in the region.

00:01:12.310 --> 00:01:17.370
Our specialists are
scholars with knowledge

00:01:17.370 --> 00:01:19.960
of the region, of the languages.

00:01:19.960 --> 00:01:23.620
We are responsible
for the collections.

00:01:23.620 --> 00:01:27.950
So we command, we
collect, we shelve,

00:01:27.950 --> 00:01:30.000
we preserve and we serve.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.210
And we serve to our
patrons materials

00:01:33.210 --> 00:01:35.880
in the languages
of those countries.

00:01:35.880 --> 00:01:40.490
So if you're doing research
on any one of those countries,

00:01:40.490 --> 00:01:44.190
the materials in those languages
are here in our stacks.

00:01:44.190 --> 00:01:48.340
But materials referring
in western languages

00:01:48.340 --> 00:01:53.460
to those countries are part
of the general collection.

00:01:53.460 --> 00:01:57.990
We always do programs,
as the one we have today,

00:01:57.990 --> 00:02:06.330
to enrich our knowledge of the
countries that we cover to share

00:02:06.330 --> 00:02:12.200
with our patrons
more information

00:02:12.200 --> 00:02:15.270
about those collections,

00:02:15.270 --> 00:02:19.670
and to show how our collections
are being used, are being used

00:02:19.670 --> 00:02:25.140
to write articles, to
write books, to inform.

00:02:25.140 --> 00:02:33.020
And many of our countries seem
often quite exotic [inaudible],

00:02:33.020 --> 00:02:36.560
having little to do
with the United States.

00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:41.920
But today's program actually
shows how those very countries

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:44.960
have had an impact and continue

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:47.950
to have an impact on
the United States.

00:02:47.950 --> 00:02:51.570
And not just culturally
or linguistically,

00:02:51.570 --> 00:02:56.280
or in terms of food or whatever,
but physically in terms

00:02:56.280 --> 00:03:00.870
of the very architecture of
the cities and the programs.

00:03:00.870 --> 00:03:06.770
And it's only by having
someone like Phil Pasquini go

00:03:06.770 --> 00:03:12.120
around the country, observe,
take pictures, and show

00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:17.780
and demonstrate the impact
of those cultures which seem

00:03:17.780 --> 00:03:26.190
so foreign to many and yet are
integrated and very much part

00:03:26.190 --> 00:03:28.940
of the United States landscape.

00:03:28.940 --> 00:03:33.840
It's only by having someone like
him show it that we understand,

00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:36.890
we get a better understanding
of really the impact

00:03:36.890 --> 00:03:40.060
of the world on the US.

00:03:40.060 --> 00:03:43.500
So in order to introduce
the speaker,

00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:47.530
we have Joan Weeks who's the
head of our [inaudible] section

00:03:47.530 --> 00:03:51.090
and also the Turkish specialist.

00:03:51.090 --> 00:03:53.600
She wears both hats.

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:59.130
And who met Phil Pasquini at
a gathering and invited him

00:03:59.130 --> 00:04:03.660
when she realized how exciting
the work he was doing is,

00:04:03.660 --> 00:04:06.470
and she wanted to share

00:04:06.470 --> 00:04:10.640
with everyone the
work that he has done.

00:04:10.640 --> 00:04:12.610
So Joan will introduce
the speaker,

00:04:12.610 --> 00:04:15.510
and thank you again all
for being here today.

00:04:15.510 --> 00:04:20.250
[ Applause ]

00:04:20.250 --> 00:04:21.590
&gt;&gt; Joan Weeks: Thank
you, Mary Jane.

00:04:21.590 --> 00:04:23.420
I'd also like to
welcome everyone.

00:04:23.420 --> 00:04:27.130
And now it is my great pleasure
to introduce our speaker.

00:04:27.130 --> 00:04:31.550
Phil Pasquini is internationally
acclaimed photo journalist.

00:04:31.550 --> 00:04:34.500
In his professional
career he has worked

00:04:34.500 --> 00:04:38.700
as a college professor in
sculpture and industrial design,

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:40.570
and has lectured
on these subjects

00:04:40.570 --> 00:04:43.030
in Europe and the Middle East.

00:04:43.030 --> 00:04:47.150
Since 1999 he has been
a staff photographer

00:04:47.150 --> 00:04:51.240
at the Washington Report
on Middle East affairs.

00:04:51.240 --> 00:04:56.240
This very interesting journal
I have here in my hands,

00:04:56.240 --> 00:04:58.370
and I invite you
to check for that.

00:04:58.370 --> 00:05:01.050
Also we have it in
our collections,

00:05:01.050 --> 00:05:03.540
and look for it as well.

00:05:03.540 --> 00:05:06.170
In his work as a
photo journalist,

00:05:06.170 --> 00:05:09.370
his photographs have appeared
in publications worldwide.

00:05:09.370 --> 00:05:13.290
He's also worked as a foreign
radio correspondent reporting

00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:16.860
from Europe and the Middle East,
and across the United States.

00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:20.330
In 2010 he received
the prestigious Council

00:05:20.330 --> 00:05:24.030
on American Islamic Relations,
CAIR Award, for fairness

00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:26.410
and integrity in the media.

00:05:26.410 --> 00:05:29.580
In 1980 he received
a national endowment

00:05:29.580 --> 00:05:32.830
for the arts individual
fellowship, which allowed him

00:05:32.830 --> 00:05:35.220
to pursue a photographic study

00:05:35.220 --> 00:05:38.550
of ancient Egyptian
art and sites in Egypt.

00:05:38.550 --> 00:05:42.600
That, to me, sounds very
exciting, to be able to be able

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:47.400
to go there and photograph
those fantastic treasures.

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:51.530
He has traveled extensively
in North America, Europe,

00:05:51.530 --> 00:05:55.320
North Africa, and the Middle
East pursuing many significant

00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:57.040
and historical news stories.

00:05:57.040 --> 00:06:00.730
His interest in Islamic
architecture first evolved

00:06:00.730 --> 00:06:03.690
from a trip to Morocco in 1970

00:06:03.690 --> 00:06:06.750
and has been an ongoing
photographic subject

00:06:06.750 --> 00:06:08.460
in his work since that time.

00:06:08.460 --> 00:06:12.570
He illustrated his book
Domes, Arches, and Minarets

00:06:12.570 --> 00:06:16.530
as well his lecture with images
from the library's prints

00:06:16.530 --> 00:06:18.690
and photographs collection.

00:06:18.690 --> 00:06:22.850
Perhaps after today's talk
you'll see reflections

00:06:22.850 --> 00:06:25.690
of Islamic architecture
around you.

00:06:25.690 --> 00:06:29.190
I, for example, as I was
preparing this, was reminded

00:06:29.190 --> 00:06:33.490
of the paintings inside the
dome of the main reading room,

00:06:33.490 --> 00:06:35.620
which attributes the areas

00:06:35.620 --> 00:06:38.930
of the world's knowledge
where they came from.

00:06:38.930 --> 00:06:43.260
And physics is attributed
to Islam.

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:45.860
So perhaps you'll see
more of these reflections

00:06:45.860 --> 00:06:47.160
as he goes through his lecture.

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:49.940
Please help me welcome
Phil to the podium.

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:51.740
Thank you.

00:06:51.740 --> 00:06:54.230
[ Applause ]

