Yeah.

00:54:59.960 --> 00:55:01.260
&gt;&gt; What is the connection?

00:55:01.260 --> 00:55:02.560
&gt;&gt; Phil Pasquini:
So it goes back

00:55:02.560 --> 00:55:05.620
to I can't remember the year,
but it was early 1900s I believe

00:55:05.620 --> 00:55:09.050
that there was a
guy who was a mason

00:55:09.050 --> 00:55:10.660
who was in Southern France.

00:55:10.660 --> 00:55:15.000
And he was invited to a party
for an oriental potentate.

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:18.110
And we got there, everybody
was in oriental dress.

00:55:18.110 --> 00:55:20.160
They had Tarboosh
fezzes [phonetic]

00:55:20.160 --> 00:55:23.870
and they had balloon
pants and turned-up shoes.

00:55:23.870 --> 00:55:25.190
And he thought this is great.

00:55:25.190 --> 00:55:28.560
This is exactly what
we need in the masons,

00:55:28.560 --> 00:55:30.810
because it's so drab and boring.

00:55:30.810 --> 00:55:32.110
And he came back to New York.

00:55:32.110 --> 00:55:33.640
And he met a fellow mason.

00:55:33.640 --> 00:55:36.750
He was an actor, and the guy
that he met was a doctor.

00:55:36.750 --> 00:55:39.340
And they decided that
they would do something.

00:55:39.340 --> 00:55:41.310
So they said, well, let's
start a separate offshoot.

00:55:41.310 --> 00:55:44.280
We'll start the Shrine,
because they were thinking

00:55:44.280 --> 00:55:45.970
about mosques and shrines.

00:55:45.970 --> 00:55:47.700
And so they started
The Shriners.

00:55:47.700 --> 00:55:49.780
And their depiction,
it's very Egyptian

00:55:49.780 --> 00:55:51.920
if you look at the symbology.

00:55:51.920 --> 00:55:55.550
They have the Spinx and then
there's the Simatar [phonetic].

00:55:55.550 --> 00:55:58.000
And when they meet somebody
they say [foreign language].

00:55:58.000 --> 00:55:59.310
And the response is
[foreign language].

00:55:59.310 --> 00:56:02.200
And they have a secret
handshake,

00:56:02.200 --> 00:56:03.790
which I haven't been
able to get to the bottom

00:56:03.790 --> 00:56:05.490
of because I don't belong.

00:56:05.490 --> 00:56:07.870
And they originally
named their buildings.

00:56:07.870 --> 00:56:12.050
And they purposely built the
buildings in an Islamic style

00:56:12.050 --> 00:56:14.360
to make them distinctive
on the landscape.

00:56:14.360 --> 00:56:18.180
And this is what German Jews
did with mosques starting

00:56:18.180 --> 00:56:19.680
in the 1850s in Germany.

00:56:19.680 --> 00:56:23.060
They decided they wanted
a distinctive style

00:56:23.060 --> 00:56:29.280
for a synagogue that would
also delineate their presence

00:56:29.280 --> 00:56:30.580
on the landscape.

00:56:30.580 --> 00:56:33.960
So The Shriners decided
to build these buildings.

00:56:33.960 --> 00:56:36.650
And when you see them,
they always have a fez on.

00:56:36.650 --> 00:56:38.610
And if you look, you
know, they have ties

00:56:38.610 --> 00:56:40.250
with pyramids and so on.

00:56:40.250 --> 00:56:43.890
So they have become really
affected by all of that,

00:56:43.890 --> 00:56:47.150
which I find really interesting
especially in today's world.

00:56:47.150 --> 00:56:49.320
And so many of these
things are disconnected.

00:56:49.320 --> 00:56:51.530
I don't know how many
people really know

00:56:51.530 --> 00:56:56.380
that a fez has orientalist
or Islamic origins

00:56:56.380 --> 00:56:59.900
or now it's been used a
sign, a symbol of repression

00:56:59.900 --> 00:57:01.850
under the Ottomans and so on.

00:57:01.850 --> 00:57:03.720
So there's all these
historical, you know,

00:57:03.720 --> 00:57:05.800
things that go on
with it was well.

00:57:05.800 --> 00:57:07.220
That's kind of a backdrop.

00:57:07.220 --> 00:57:10.330
And I do go into the history
of The Shrine in the book,

00:57:10.330 --> 00:57:12.140
because I wanted to
contextualize that as part

00:57:12.140 --> 00:57:15.130
of this history as it
evolves and moves forward.

00:57:15.130 --> 00:57:17.060
But they're significant.

00:57:17.060 --> 00:57:21.370
And since doing the book, I
think I found over 235 buildings

00:57:21.370 --> 00:57:23.180
that are still existing
in this style.

00:57:23.180 --> 00:57:25.210
So they're pretty
much everywhere.

00:57:25.210 --> 00:57:28.270
And a lot of people will say
to me afterwards, you know,

00:57:28.270 --> 00:57:31.370
I was in Philadelphia and I
was going down this street.

00:57:31.370 --> 00:57:34.110
And after I saw what
you had in that book,

00:57:34.110 --> 00:57:35.410
I saw this other building.

00:57:35.410 --> 00:57:36.980
So these people have
become, you know,

00:57:36.980 --> 00:57:39.820
sensitized to opening their
eyes and seeing these things,

00:57:39.820 --> 00:57:43.200
which I think is really
positive, you know, good thing.

00:57:45.030 --> 00:57:46.330
Yes?

00:57:46.330 --> 00:57:51.560
&gt;&gt; On a more contemporary level,
I know when you go down I-75,

00:57:51.560 --> 00:57:56.920
Toledo, Cleveland, there's a
big mosque there on the side

00:57:56.920 --> 00:58:00.810
of the highway of I-75.

00:58:00.810 --> 00:58:02.200
Are you familiar with that one?

00:58:02.200 --> 00:58:03.500
&gt;&gt; Phil Pasquini: No, I'm not.

