00:58:52.540 --> 00:58:53.840
&gt;&gt; Phil Pasquini:
Yeah, they do, okay.

00:58:53.840 --> 00:58:55.140
Yeah, I thought it
was connected.

00:58:55.140 --> 00:58:56.440
That's cool.

00:58:56.440 --> 00:58:57.740
That's a good building.

00:58:57.740 --> 00:58:59.040
Yes, Joan?

00:58:59.040 --> 00:59:00.340
&gt;&gt; Joan Weeks: I'm just
absolutely fascinated with all

00:59:00.340 --> 00:59:01.890
of the way, his stories
behind his buildings

00:59:01.890 --> 00:59:04.950
and how he uncovered
some of those stories.

00:59:04.950 --> 00:59:11.070
[Inaudible] historical societies
or have you come across people

00:59:11.070 --> 00:59:14.590
who kind of remember how
these things [inaudible].

00:59:14.590 --> 00:59:17.060
&gt;&gt; Phil Pasquini: It really
somewhat serendipitous and a lot

00:59:17.060 --> 00:59:22.110
of hard work, and a lot of
Googling, a lot of reading,

00:59:22.110 --> 00:59:25.010
a lot of looking at maps
that were located in the map

00:59:25.010 --> 00:59:29.750
and geography division in
The Library of Congress.

00:59:29.750 --> 00:59:31.560
And then just a lot of
real hard searching.

00:59:31.560 --> 00:59:34.020
And in some cases, I was able to
find the architect of buildings

00:59:34.020 --> 00:59:35.740
that nobody knew who
the architect was.

00:59:35.740 --> 00:59:38.770
It had gotten lost in
historical records.

00:59:38.770 --> 00:59:40.800
Some people, when I went to the
building, they said, oh, yeah,

00:59:40.800 --> 00:59:42.100
we love this building.

00:59:42.100 --> 00:59:44.230
It's the only one
in the US like it.

00:59:44.230 --> 00:59:47.160
And I felt terrible telling
them no, it's one of many.

00:59:47.160 --> 00:59:48.940
But it was a good learning
experience for them,

00:59:48.940 --> 00:59:50.890
because then they
realized that, you know,

00:59:50.890 --> 00:59:54.690
Islamic design has been
part of American culture

00:59:54.690 --> 00:59:57.420
for a very long time,
before we were a country.

00:59:57.420 --> 01:00:02.490
And so, you know, they somewhat
came more around to thinking

01:00:02.490 --> 01:00:04.520
about these things
as not threatening,

01:00:04.520 --> 01:00:06.290
but as part of a
historical thing.

01:00:06.290 --> 01:00:08.890
But a lot of reading.

01:00:08.890 --> 01:00:11.460
I met a lot of wonderful
people who are caretakers

01:00:11.460 --> 01:00:13.170
for the buildings, who
are really into it.

01:00:13.170 --> 01:00:16.150
Many of them had stories.

01:00:16.150 --> 01:00:20.820
Holler Nutt's Building
in Natchez.

01:00:20.820 --> 01:00:23.010
I met a woman who lived
there, when she was a kid,

01:00:23.010 --> 01:00:26.010
because her aunt was
a descendant of Nutt.

01:00:26.010 --> 01:00:29.540
And they lived there as a
child and tourists would come.

01:00:29.540 --> 01:00:30.970
And she'd tell people,
oh, don't go in that room.

01:00:30.970 --> 01:00:32.270
There's a ghost in there.

01:00:32.270 --> 01:00:33.570
And these people are,
oh, my God, you know.

01:00:33.570 --> 01:00:36.580
And so they had their
own interpretation

01:00:36.580 --> 01:00:37.880
and depiction of the building.

01:00:37.880 --> 01:00:41.290
So I did learn quite a lot from
people who owned the buildings.

01:00:41.290 --> 01:00:44.530
And then I tried to,
each plate in the book,

01:00:44.530 --> 01:00:46.890
there on the left
side there's the names

01:00:46.890 --> 01:00:49.560
of the building's been known
under, the year of construction,

01:00:49.560 --> 01:00:52.100
the style, the architects'
names, and then whether

01:00:52.100 --> 01:00:53.880
or not it's something
historical,

01:00:53.880 --> 01:00:56.530
the National Registry
for Historical Buildings.

01:00:56.530 --> 01:00:59.530
And then I put as much as
the history that I could find

01:00:59.530 --> 01:01:01.720
about the building
there as well,

01:01:01.720 --> 01:01:04.500
and then on the right side
is the full photograph

01:01:04.500 --> 01:01:05.800
of the structure.

01:01:05.800 --> 01:01:08.620
So it acts both as the
historical reference

01:01:08.620 --> 01:01:09.990
and a catalog of
these buildings.

01:01:09.990 --> 01:01:14.880
Some, as I said, are in bad
shape and need rehabilitation.

01:01:14.880 --> 01:01:16.340
But it was a labor of love.

01:01:16.340 --> 01:01:20.570
It took me five years, and we
traveled around at 25 states.

01:01:20.570 --> 01:01:25.060
And then we'd have to stay in
a town at least four days just

01:01:25.060 --> 01:01:27.520
so I could shoot buildings at
different times of the day.

01:01:27.520 --> 01:01:28.910
And one day it would rain,

01:01:28.910 --> 01:01:30.790
the next day the sun
would be out, you know.

01:01:30.790 --> 01:01:34.040
The usual thing, trying to catch
everything in its perfect light.

01:01:34.040 --> 01:01:37.440
So a labor of love it's been.

01:01:37.440 --> 01:01:39.020
&gt;&gt; So how did you [inaudible].

01:01:39.020 --> 01:01:42.200
I mean what was your approach?

01:01:42.200 --> 01:01:44.860
As you said, you went to
these five different states.

01:01:44.860 --> 01:01:48.240
So did you know already that
these buildings were there

01:01:48.240 --> 01:01:52.880
or did you discover them, or
how did you find out about them?

01:01:52.880 --> 01:01:54.200
&gt;&gt; Phil Pasquini: Well,
I did a lot of research.

01:01:54.200 --> 01:01:56.190
So, for example, I
went to Tennessee

01:01:56.190 --> 01:01:58.560
to photograph a number
of buildings.

01:01:58.560 --> 01:02:01.110
And I was driving back
to the hotel in Memphis.

01:02:01.110 --> 01:02:03.000
And I went, oh, my God, look.

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:05.240
Here's this beautiful Islamic
building I knew nothing

01:02:05.240 --> 01:02:06.540
about it.

01:02:06.540 --> 01:02:07.840
It's now a law office,

01:02:07.840 --> 01:02:09.700
but it was an apartment
house I think originally.

01:02:09.700 --> 01:02:11.270
So somewhat serendipitous.

01:02:11.270 --> 01:02:15.530
The one I talked about with the
inventor of the soldering iron,

01:02:15.530 --> 01:02:17.490
we were walking down
the street in Rapid City

01:02:17.490 --> 01:02:19.080
and turned the corner,
and here's this building.

01:02:19.080 --> 01:02:22.070
You know, it was almost maybe
divine intervention I was pulled

01:02:22.070 --> 01:02:23.410
to these buildings.

01:02:23.410 --> 01:02:25.830
So it was a combination of
both, of concerted effort

01:02:25.830 --> 01:02:29.150
and in a few instances
just happening upon things.

01:02:29.150 --> 01:02:31.900
Or someone would tell me, well,
if you like this building,

01:02:31.900 --> 01:02:34.780
you should see the one, you
know, five blocks over there.

01:02:34.780 --> 01:02:37.370
And I'd go and it would
either be an Islamic building

01:02:37.370 --> 01:02:40.040
or it could be a Russian
Orthodox church or something,

01:02:40.040 --> 01:02:41.430
you know, not connected.

01:02:41.430 --> 01:02:44.830
But it had some of the same
similar architectural details.

01:02:44.830 --> 01:02:48.880
And so that's a good question
and it did evolve in some ways.

01:02:48.880 --> 01:02:50.180
Yes?

01:02:50.180 --> 01:02:53.640
&gt;&gt; So what was your
original inspiration?

01:02:53.640 --> 01:02:55.350
Did you go to Morocco first?

01:02:55.350 --> 01:02:57.820
&gt;&gt; Phil Pasquini: In
1970, I went to Morocco

01:02:57.820 --> 01:02:59.940
and it seemed very exotic to me.

01:02:59.940 --> 01:03:01.240
And only later did I find

01:03:01.240 --> 01:03:04.050
out that my mother's family
had lived there 500 years

01:03:04.050 --> 01:03:09.830
in the year 1010 to
about 1121, or something.

01:03:09.830 --> 01:03:12.200
So that kind of pulled
me into it.

01:03:12.200 --> 01:03:15.130
But I always liked
Islamic styled things,

01:03:15.130 --> 01:03:16.690
because it seemed
so exotic to me.

01:03:16.690 --> 01:03:18.460
And as a kid growing
up in Sacramento,

01:03:18.460 --> 01:03:21.080
California where
there's really nothing.

01:03:21.080 --> 01:03:23.540
And I went to El Hambra
Theater when I was a kid,

01:03:23.540 --> 01:03:25.130
and it was orientalist.

01:03:25.130 --> 01:03:28.050
And that totally, you
know, got my interest.

01:03:28.050 --> 01:03:30.080
I did the book, as I said
earlier, because I wanted

01:03:30.080 --> 01:03:34.420
to dispel the notion that
this call came about on 911,

01:03:34.420 --> 01:03:38.810
that Muslims arrived in
America with nefarious intents.

01:03:38.810 --> 01:03:41.780
And I wanted to contextualize
that history properly

01:03:41.780 --> 01:03:43.750
in the sense that
Muslims have been

01:03:43.750 --> 01:03:45.980
in America before it
was even a country.

01:03:45.980 --> 01:03:49.290
And we know that
historically on many levels.

01:03:49.290 --> 01:03:50.870
And there's a wonderful book,

01:03:50.870 --> 01:03:53.790
and I can't recollect
the title of it now.

01:03:53.790 --> 01:03:59.250
But in it, he talks about the
history of music and poetry

01:03:59.250 --> 01:04:03.210
and dance and design and many
things that have Islamic roots.

01:04:03.210 --> 01:04:08.850
Mathematics, for example, that
are not often credited properly

01:04:08.850 --> 01:04:12.550
and seem as a construct of
Western European invention,

01:04:12.550 --> 01:04:14.310
and we know that not to be true.

01:04:14.310 --> 01:04:16.570
It's always interesting
when people are arguing

01:04:16.570 --> 01:04:18.920
about diversity, and
they pick up a newspaper

01:04:18.920 --> 01:04:22.290
and I think you're reading
something in the Latin alphabet

01:04:22.290 --> 01:04:23.800
and you're looking
at Arabic numerals.

01:04:23.800 --> 01:04:26.530
I don't know how more
diverse that can be.

01:04:26.530 --> 01:04:29.070
So we kind of remove
ourselves from these things.

01:04:29.070 --> 01:04:30.370
Does that answer your question?

01:04:30.370 --> 01:04:31.670
&gt;&gt; It does.

